{"id": "duc04-testb-15:1#5", "contents": "Despite these concerns, experts argue that hate crime laws do not impinge on freedom of speech and are necessary to send a clear message that society does not tolerate attacks on minorities. Brian Levin, a criminal justice professor, notes that hate crime laws have been enacted in 40 states without restricting free speech and that they are essential in deterring violent crimes against minorities. He also points out that homosexuals suffer higher rates of violent crime than the general population and that many attackers are young men."}
